The paper focuses on the design of wireless networks using artificial intelligence and guided learning, which falls under the category of computer networks (cs.NI). The use of AI and learning algorithms to optimize network configuration suggests that the paper may also belong to the sub-categories of artificial intelligence (cs.AI) and machine learning (cs.LG). The self-optimizing and self-learning framework proposed in the paper also involves system and environment evolution, which could be relevant to the sub-category of control systems (cs.SY). Finally, the paper addresses the non-deterministic polynomial-time hardness (NP-hard) problem of joint channel assignment and location optimization in wireless mesh networks, which could be related to the sub-category of information theory (cs.IT).
